/names/n42025618 0aUnited States congressional serial set ;vserial no. 8533.0https://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n9204865440uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo162036704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/SERIALSET-08533_00_00-120-1010-0000/pdf/SERIALSET-08533_00_00-120-1010-0000.pdf  a92bGPO  aSERIALSET-08533_00_00-120-1010-0000b08533_00_00c120g1010h0000  aSERIALSETDELIVERY204991cai a2200685 i 00116066620260409084543.0m     o  d f      cr mn|||||||||210203c20219999dcu x w o b  f0    2eng c  a2021235709  a(OCoLC)1236002329  aDIDbengerdaepncDIDdOCLCOdOCLCFdGPOdOCLCOdOCLCQdCOMdOCLCOdOCLdGPO  apcc  an-us---  aGPOO  a0807-A-07 (online)0 aLC 14.23:R 46662/1 aCho, Clare Y.,eauthor.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no20200956761https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjHYgBm9yv73yCgTpm7gVd10aSocial media :bcontent dissemination and moderation practices /cClare Y. Cho, Ling Zhu.10aSocial media :bmisinformation and content moderation issues for Congress / Jason A. Gallo, Clare Y. Chof<February 3, 2021>  a[Library of Congress public edition]. 1a[Washington, D.C.] :bCongressional Research Service,c2021-  a1 online resource.  aUpdated irregularly  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aReport / Congressional Research Service ;vR46662  aThe CRS web page provides access to all versions published since 2018 in accordance with P.L. 115-141.  aReport includes bibliographical references.  aSocial media platforms disseminate information quickly to billions of global users. The Pew Research Center estimates that in 2019, 72% of U.S. adults used at least one social media site and that the majority of users visited the site at least once a week. Some Members of Congress are concerned about the spread of misinformation (i.e., incorrect or inaccurate information) on social media platforms and are exploring how it can be addressed by companies that operate social media sites. Other Members are concerned that social media operators' content moderation practices may suppress speech. Both perspectives have focused on Section 230 of the Communications Act of 1934 (47 U.S.C. §230), enacted as part of the Communications Decency Act of 1996, which broadly protects operators of "interactive computer services" from liability for publishing, removing, or restricting access to another's content. Congress may wish to consider the roles of the public and private sector in addressing misinformation, including who defines what constitutes misinformation. If Congress determines that action to address the spread of misinformation through social media is necessary, its options may be limited by the reality that regulation, policies, or incentives to affect one category of information may affect others. Congress may consider the First Amendment implications of potential legislative actions. Any effort to address this issue may have unintended legal, social, and economic consequences that may be difficult to foresee.0 aContents viewed Nov. 20, 2025; title from CRS web page.  aAlso available to subscribers of CQ.com via the World Wide Web; files in PDF. 0aSocial mediaxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDisinformationzUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 0aSocial responsibility of businesszUnited States. 7aFreedom of speech.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00934044 7aSocial mediaxLaw and legislation.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01767818 7aSocial responsibility of business.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01122851 7aUnited States.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01204155 7aBibliographies.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01919895 2aBibliography.0(DNLM)D016417 7aBibliographies.2lcgft0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/genreForms/gf20140260481 aGallo, Jason A.,eauthor.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no20210847651https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjwBRXtpyrX69fc9bXhCQq1 aZhu, Lingc(Analyst in telecommuni