 800aSite selection decision: Federal Bureau of Investigation suburban headquarters: National Capital Region.30aFederal Bureau of Investigation suburban headquarters, National Capital Region 1a[Washington, D.C.] :bGeneral Services Administration,c2023.  a1 online resource (38 pages) :bcolor illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (gsa, viewed April 29, 2026).10aUnited States.bFederal Bureau of Investigation. 0aBuildingszUnited States.1 aUnited States.bGeneral Services Administration,eissuing body.40uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo255456704 uhttps://www.gsa.gov/system/files/FBI%20HQ%20Site%20Selection%20Decision.pdf  aC0bGPO  abc106 20260429b20260429  aUNREPORTEDPUBSASKGPOb20260112  abc106 2026042903572cam a2200541 i 00147189720260430084206.0m     o  d f      cr |||||||||||260116s2025    aluab   ob   f000 0 eng c  a(OCoLC)1569075950  aAAUbengerdaepncAAUdOCLCOdGPO  apcc  aa-cc---aa-ii---  aXZL4  a0422-K (online)0 aD 301.26/6:T 43/21 aVan Oudenaren, John,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjJRyjGKB88MfvF9bpRmgq10aRemote basing :bPeople's Liberation Army logistics on the Tibetan Plateau /cprepared by BluePath Labs ; John S. Van Oudenaren.30aPeople's Liberation Army logistics on the Tibetan Plateau3 aPLA's logistics on the Tibetan Plateau 1aMontgomery, AL :bChina Aerospace Studies Institute,c2025.  a1 online resource (57 pages) :bcolor illustrations, color maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atextbPDF2rdaft  a"November 2025."  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 43-57).0 aIntroduction -- PLA force structure amd logistical support in Tibet -- Remote basing: Logistical support methods.  a"The People's Liberation Army (PLA) is at the forefront of China's efforts to defend its extensive land border with India and maintain firm control over Tibet. As both China and India have expanded their respective infrastructural and military basing networks along the Line of Actual Control (the sectors of the Sino-Indian border where demarcation remains disputed), significant escalations have occurred, most notably the Doklam Standoff in mid-2017 and the Galwan Valley skirmish in June 2020. For the PLA, providing logistical support and sustainment to troops stationed on the "roof of the world" is a longstanding challenge. Nevertheless, despite the generally difficult geography on the Chinese side of the border, more effective logistical support appears to remain an enduring advantage for the PLA over the Indian Armed Forces."--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF cover (airuniversity.af.edu, viewed April 16, 2026).10aChina.bZhongguo ren min jie fang junxProcurement. 0aMilitary baseszTibetan Plateau. 0aChinaxForeign relationszIndia. 0aIndiaxForeign relationszChina. 6aChine0(CaQQLa)201-0053864xRelations extérieures0(CaQQLa)201-0053864zInde.0(CaQQLa)201-0482676 6aInde0(CaQQLa)201-0156737xRelations extérieures0(CaQQLa)201-0156737zChine.0(CaQQLa)201-04766192 aChina Aerospace Studies Institute (U.S.),eissuing body.2 aBluePath Labs (Firm)40uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo255294704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://www.airuniversity.af.edu/Portals/10/CASI/documents/Research/Infrastructure/2025-11-03%20Remote%20Basing.pdf?ver=TltuET9d7FpS2QdQx2ZUMw%3d%3d  aC0bGPO  abc108 20260430b20260430  aBIBCONEWb20260430  aUNREPORTEDPUBSASKGPOb2026043005986cam a2200553 i 00147189920260430084941.0m     o  d f      cr |||||||||||260116s2025    alud    obr  f000 0 eng c  a(OCoLC)1569046647  aAAUbengerdaepncAAUdOCLCOdGPO  aengachi  apcc  aa-cc---  aXZL4  a0422-K (onlline)0 aD 301.26/6:L 11/2/20251 aBruzzese, Matt,eauthor.10aChina's defense S&T key lab system /cprepared by BluePath Labs ; by Matthew Bruzzese.3 aChina's defense science and technology key lab system  a2025 update. 1aMontgomery, AL :bChina Aerospace Studies Institute,c2025.  a1 online resource (iv, 719 pages) :bcharts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atextbPDF2rdaft  a"October 2025"--Page 2 of cover.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 541-719).0 aOverview of defense S&T key labs -- Notes on the data presented in the directory -- Lab data -- Known former defense S&T key laboratories.  a"This report represents an updated and significantly expanded revision of The PRC State & Defense Laboratory System Part Two: Defense S&T Key Lab Directory, which was released in early 2023. That report was in turn the second part of The PRC State & Defense Laboratory System: An Overview, which was released in 2022 and described the general structure and organization of the PRC's state research system. Cumulatively, these reports focus on the PRC's Defense S&T Key Laboratories (DSTKLs), first established in 1991 as the PRC's highest-level network of military labs. As the military counterpart to the PRC's top-level State Key Lab (SKL) system, these labs receive the most funding and conduct what the PRC considers to be its most critical military research. In the previous edition of this report, CASI utilized a list of 60 DSTKLs circulating on the internet, apparently from a since-deleted PRC government website.^Accounting for duplicates and labs since downgraded in status left a sample of 56 labs. Extensive open-source research was conducted on each of these labs, providing details on each lab's research foci, real-world applications of that research, funding, facilities and equipment, domestic and international collaborations, leadership and personnel, aliases, and any other information which may be of interest to researchers of PRC defense technology. For this updated edition of the report, we added another 42 Defense S&T Key Labs, increasing the number of known DSTKLs by more than 40 percent. The same level of research was applied to these additional labs, bringing the total number of DSTKLs profiled in this report from 56 to 98. In addition, we recalculated the statistics presented in Part One of this report to incorporate these new labs.^Some labs contained considerably more information than others; some were very public-facing, with official websites and no shortage of laudatory state media coverage of their work, while others offered very little public information at all. Generally, university-run labs tended to be more open about their work than state-owned enterprise (SOE) labs, and military-run labs had less public information than either of these. The 42 additional labs profiled for the first time in this edition of the report tended, on the whole, to have less information publicly available (which in some cases is likely how they have managed to fly under the radar), although this was not true in all cases. This work is intended primarily as a guide and reference work for analysts of PRC science and technology, translating detailed information on all of the PRC's known Defense S&T Key Labs and gathering it in one place for the first time.^While it shows what PRC officials and researchers emphasize in terms of research priorities, it is not intended to make qualitative judgements about their progress in this research. Much of the material in this report is comprised of dense technical jargon which requires analysis by specialists in that field and which may pose translation challenges. However, we have included such information in the hope that it will provide useful insights into the state and priorities of PRC strategic research when read by analysts who possess the requisite knowledge. CASI hopes that this data will both provide greater insight into the inner workings and priorities of DSTKLs, and also raise awareness of these labs and their attempts to collaborate with U.S. institutions."--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF cover (airuniversity.af.edu, viewed April 16, 2026). 0aLaboratorieszChinavDirectories. 0aMilitary researchzChinavDirectories. 0aCivil-military relationszChinavDirectories. 6aRecherche militaire0(CaQQLa)201-0020984zChine.0(CaQQLa)201-0476619 6aLaboratoires0(CaQQLa)201-0075879zChine.0(CaQQLa)201-0476619 6aRelations pouvoir civil-pouvoir militaire0(CaQQLa)201-0025638zChine.0(CaQQLa)201-0476619 7aDirectories.2lcgft2 aChina Aerospace Studies Institute (U.S.),eissuing body.2 aBluePath Labs (Firm)08iRevision of:aXiu, Ma (Area specialist).tPRC state & defense laboratory systemw(OCoLC)138866784240uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo255290704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://www.airuniversity.af.edu/Portals/10/CASI/documents/Research/Infrastructure/2025-10-20%20Defense%20Labs%20Directory.pdf?ver=Pf6vZK5cF_fyZiHS9Sjc2g%3d%3d  aC0bGPO  abc108 20260430b20260430  aBIBCONEWb20260430  aUNREPORTEDPUBSASKGPOb2026043002298cam a2200469 i 00147191520260504153313.0m     o  d f      cr |||||||||||260430s2024    dcua    ob   f000 0 eng c  a(OCoLC)1587443710  aGPObengerdaepncGPOdGPO  apcc  an-us---  aGPOO  a0445-L-15 (online)0 aHE 23.1218/2:P 8400aPostsecondary support for students who have been in foster care. 1a[Washington, D.C.] :bU.S. Department of Health and Hum